{"parse":{"title":"and","pageid":2067,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"and\"}}\n{{minitoc}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{clip|mul|en:'''An'''sus}} with {{m|mul|d}} as a placeholder.\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|3}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{a|en|stressed}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈænd/|[ˈænd]|a=non-æ-raising}}\n*** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Pvanp7-and (stressed).wav|a=UK}}\n** {{a|en|æ-raising}}\n*** {{IPA|en|/ˈeə̯nd/|[ˈeə̯nd]|;|/ˈɛə̯nd/|[ˈɛə̯nd]|a=US,CA}}\n**** {{audio|en|en-us-and.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈənd/|[ˈənd]|;|[n̩d]|;|[n̩ʔ]|a=unstressed}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Pvanp7-and (unstressed).wav|a=UK}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-and (unstressed).wav|a=Southern England}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-ham-and-eggs.ogg|a=US|text=ham and eggs|IPA=/ˈhɛə̯m‿n̩‿ɛɡz/}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ænd|s=1}}<!-- NOTE: Do not add /ənd/, /ən/, etc. rhymes: no rhymes with an unstressed word.-->\n* {{hyph|en|and}}\n* {{hmp|en|an<qq:unstressed>|ant<qq:in some accents>|end<qq:in some accents>|in<qq:unstressed>}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|en|id=conjunction|:inh|enm:and<id:conjunction>|tree=1}}\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*h₂en-}}\n{{inh+|en|enm|and}}, {{m|enm|an}}, from {{inh|en|ang|and}}, {{m|ang|ond}}, {{m|ang|end}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*andi}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*andi}}, {{m|gem-pro|*anþi}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*h₂énti||facing opposite, near, in front of, before}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|an||and}}, {{cog|frr|än||and}}, {{cog|stq|un||and}}, {{cog|fy|en||and}}, {{cog|nl|en}}, {{m|nl|ende||and}}, {{cog|de|und||and}}, {{cog|nds-de|on}}, {{m|nds-de|un||and}}, {{cog|lb|an||and}}, {{cog|wym|an}}, {{m|wym|ana||and}}, {{cog|yi|און}}, {{m|yi|אונ}}, {{m|yi|אונד}}, {{m|yi|אונ׳||and}}, {{cog|da|end||still; ever; even}}, {{cog|fo|enn||still, yet}}, {{cog|is|en||and}}, {{m|is|enn||still, yet}}, {{cog|nb|enn||and}}, {{cog|nn|en}}, {{m|nn|enn||and}}, {{cog|sv|än||still, yet}}, {{cog|sq|edhe||and}} (dialectal {{m|sq|[[ênde]], [[ênne]]}}), {{m|sq|ende||still, yet, therefore}}, {{cog|la|ante||opposite, in front of}}, {{cog|grc|ἀντί||opposite, facing}}. {{doublet|en|an}} (\"if\").\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{l|en|an'}}\n* {{l|en|'n'}} ({{l|en|n}})\n\n====Conjunction====\n{{en-head|conj}}\n\n# As a coordinating conjunction; expressing two elements to be taken together or in addition to each other.\n## Used simply to connect two noun phrases, adjectives or adverbs. {{defdate|from 8th c.}}\n##* '''c. 1430''' (reprinted '''1888'''), Thomas Austin, ed., ''Two Fifteenth-century Cookery-books. Harleian ms. 279 (ab. 1430), & Harl. ms. 4016 (ab. 1450), with Extracts from Ashmole ms. 1429, Laud ms. 553, & Douce ms. 55'' [Early English Text Society, Original Series; 91], London: [[w:Routledge|N. Trübner & Co.]] for the {{w|Early English Text Society}}, volume I, <small>[[w:Online Computer Library Center|OCLC]] [http://worldcat.org/oclc/374760 374760]</small>, page 11:\n##*: Soupes dorye. — Take gode almaunde mylke {{...}} caste þher-to Safroun '''an''' Salt {{...}}\n##* {{RQ:Shakespeare Merchant of Venice|V|1|text=Sweet lady, you have given me life '''and''' living; {{...}}}}\n##* {{RQ:King James Version|Genesis|1|1|passage=In the beginning God created the heaven '''and''' the earth.}}\n##* {{RQ:Austen Persuasion|text=as for Mrs. Smith, she had claims of various kinds to recommend her quickly '''and''' permanently.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|date=5 November 2011|author=Mark Townsend|journal=The Guardian\n|passage=‘The UKBA has some serious explaining to do if it is routinely carrying out such abusive '''and''' unlawful inspections.’}}\n## Simply connecting two clauses or sentences. {{defdate|from 8th c.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1991|author=w:Jung Chang|title=Wild Swans\n|passage=When she saw several boys carrying a huge wooden case full of porcelain, she mumbled to Jinming that she was going to have a look, '''and''' left the room.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|date=5 November 2011|author=Helena Smith; Tom Kington|journal=The Guardian\n|passage=\"Consensus is essential for the country,\" he said, adding that he was not \"tied\" to his post '''and''' was willing to step aside.}}\n## Introducing a clause or sentence which follows on in time or consequence from the first. {{defdate|from 9th c.}}\n##: ''I'd been walking since sunrise, '''and''' I was hungry.''\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1996|author=David Beasley|title=Chocolate for the Poor\n|passage=‘But if you think you can get it, Christian, you're a fool. Set one foot upcountry '''and''' I'll kill you.’}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|date=22 August 2004|author=Will Buckley|journal=The Observer\n|passage=One more error '''and''' all the good work she had done on Friday would be for nought.}}\n##* '''2007''': [[w:Jimmy Carr|Jimmy Carr]], ''[[w:8 out of 10 Cats|8 out of 10 Cats]]'', 13th day of July episode\n##*: Romance ''is'' dead; men killed it, '''and''' made women clean up the mess.\n## {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[yet|Yet]]; [[but]]. {{defdate|10th|17th c.}}\n##* {{RQ:KJV|Matthew|XXII|text=Hee said, I goe sir, '''and''' went not.}}\n## Used to connect certain numbers: connecting units when they precede tens {{qualifier|now dated}}; connecting shillings to pence in a monetary quantity {{qualifier|now historical}}; connecting tens and units to hundreds, thousands etc. (now often omitted in US); to connect fractions to wholes. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}\n##* {{RQ:Lincoln Gettysburg|Bliss|1|passage=Four score '''and''' seven years ago our fathers brought forth, on this continent, a new nation, conceived in Liberty, and dedicated to the proposition that all men are created equal.}}\n##* {{RQ:Sinclair Jungle|chapter=26|passage=In Chicago these latter were receiving, for the most part, eighteen '''and''' a half cents an hour, and the unions wished to make this the general wage for the next year.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1915|author={{w|W. Somerset Maugham}}|title=Of Human Bondage|chapter=13\n|passage=[H]e had bought the pen-holder during his last holidays at Blackstable for one '''and''' two-pence.}}\n##* '''1956''', {{w|Dodie Smith}}, (title):\n##*: The One Hundred '''and''' One Dalmatians.\n## {{lb|en|now|colloquial|or|literary}} Used to connect more than two elements together in a chain, sometimes to stress the number of elements.\n##* {{RQ:Shakespeare Julius Caesar|II|2|text=And these does she apply, for warnings '''and''' portents, / '''And''' euils imminent; and on her knee / Hath begg'd, that I will stay at home to day.}}\n##* '''1939''', Langley, Ryerson & Woolf, ''The Wizard of Oz'' (screenplay):\n##*: Lions, '''and''' tigers, '''and''' bears! Oh, my!\n## Connecting two identical elements, with implications of continued or infinite repetition. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}\n##* {{RQ:KJV|Psalms|CXLV|text=I will extol thee, my God, O king; and I will bless thy name for ever '''and''' ever.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|date=18 March 2011|author=Jonathan Watts|journal=The Guardian\n|passage=He was at work in a nearby city when the tsunami struck. ‘As soon as I saw it, I called home. It rang '''and''' rang, but there was no answer.’}}\n## Introducing a [[parenthetical]] or explanatory clause. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1918|author=w:George W. E. Russell|title=Prime Ministers and Some Others\n|passage=The word \"capable\" occurs in Mr. Fisher's Bill, '''and''' rightly, because our mental and physical capacities are infinitely varied.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|journal=The Guardian|date=29 Jan 2008\n|passage=President Pervez Musharraf is undoubtedly sincere in his belief that he, '''and''' he alone, can save Pakistan from the twin perils of terrorism and anarchy.}}\n## Introducing the continuation of narration from a previous understood point; also used alone as a question: ‘and so what?’.\n##* {{RQ:KJV|Revelation|XIV|text='''And''' I heard a voice from heaven, as the voice of many waters, and as the voice of a great thunder: and I heard the voice of harpers harping with their harps{{nb...}}.}}\n##* {{RQ:Dickens Great Expectations|text=‘You take it smoothly now,’ said I, ‘but you were very serious last night, when you swore it was Death.’ ‘'''And''' so I swear it is Death,’ said he, putting his pipe back in his mouth{{nb...}}.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1914|author=w:Saki; ‘The Lull’|title=Beasts and Superbeasts\n|passage=‘'''And''', Vera,’ added Mrs. Durmot, turning to her sixteen-year-old niece, ‘be careful what colour ribbon you wear in your hair{{nb...}}.’}}\n## {{lb|en|now|dialectal|_|or somewhat|_|colloquial}} Used to connect two verbs where the second is dependent on the first: ‘[[to]]’. Used especially after {{m|en|come}}, {{m|en|go}} and {{m|en|try}}. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}\n##* {{RQ:Austen Sanditon|text=Beyond paying her a few charming compliments and amusing her with gay conversation, had he done anything at all to try '''and''' gain her affection?}}\n##* {{RQ:Thackeray Vanity Fair|passage=\"What have you a been '''and''' given Pitt's wife?\" said the individual in ribbons, when Pitt and Lady Jane had taken leave of the old gentleman.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1989|author=w:James Kelman|title=A Disaffection\n|passage=Remember '''and''' help yourself to the soup! called Gavin.}}\n## Introducing a [[qualitative]] difference between things having the same name; \"as well as other\". {{defdate|from 16th c.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1936|title=The Labour Monthly|volume=XVIII\n|passage=Undoubtedly every party makes mistakes. But there are mistakes '''and''' mistakes.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1972|title=Esquire|volume=LXXVIII\n|passage=\"There are managers '''and''' there are managers,\" he tells me. \"I'm totally involved in every aspect of Nina's career.\"}}\n## Used to combine numbers in [[addition]]; [[plus]] (with singular or plural verb). {{defdate|from 17th c.}}\n##: ''Two '''and''' two is/are four''.\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1791|author=w:James Boswell|title=Life of Samuel Johnson\n|passage=‘Nobody attempts to dispute that two '''and''' two make four: but with contests concerning moral truth, human passions are generally mixed{{nb...}}.’}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1871|author=w:Lewis Carroll|title=Through the Looking-Glass, and What Alice Found There\n|passage=‘Can you do Addition?’ the White Queen asked. ‘What's one '''and''' one '''and''' one '''and''' one '''and''' one '''and''' one '''and''' one '''and''' one '''and''' one '''and''' one?’}}\n# {{lb|en|heading}} ''Expressing a condition.''\n## {{lb|en|now|US|_|dialect}} [[if|If]]; provided that. {{defdate|from 13th c.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1485|author=Sir Thomas Malory|title=Le Morte Darthur|section=Book VII\n|passage=\"Where ys Sir Launcelot?\" seyde King Arthure. \"'''And''' he were here, he wolde nat grucche to do batayle for you.\"}}\n##* {{RQ:Tyndale NT|Matthew|XIV|text=Peter answered, and sayde: master, '''and''' thou be he, bidde me come unto the on the water.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1958|author=w:Shirley Ann Grau|title=The Hard Blue Sky\n|passage=\"'''And''' he went slower,\" Mike said softly, \"he go better.\"}}\n## {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[as if|As if]], [[as though]]. {{defdate|15th|17th c.}}\n##* {{RQ:Shakespeare Midsummer|I|2|text=I will roare you, '''and''' 'twere any Nightingale.}}\n##* {{RQ:Bacon Essayes|chapter=Of Innovations|passage=As they will set an house on fire, '''and''' it were but to roast their eggs.}}\n# {{lb|en|mathematics|logic}} Connecting two [[well-formed formula|well-formed formulas]] to create a new well-formed formula that requires it to only be true when both of the two formulas are true.\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n{{col-top|2|Usage notes}}\nBeginning a sentence with {{m|en|and}} or other coordinating conjunctions is considered incorrect by classical grammarians arguing that a coordinating conjunction at the start of a sentence has nothing to connect, but use of the word in this way is very common. The practice will be found in literature from Anglo-Saxon times onwards, especially as an aid to continuity in narrative and dialogue. The ''OED'' provides examples from the 9th century to the 19th century, including one from Shakespeare’s ''King John:'' “''Arthur''. Must you with hot Irons, burne out both mine eyes? ''Hubert.'' Young boy, I must. ''Arthur''. And will you? ''Hubert''. And I will.” It is also used for other rhetorical purposes, especially to denote surprise\n\n<blockquote>(O John! and you have seen him! And are you really going?—1884 in ''OED'') </blockquote>\n\nand sometimes just to introduce an improvised afterthought\n\n<blockquote>(I’m going to swim. And don’t you dare watch—G. Butler, 1983)</blockquote>\n\nIt is, however, poor style to separate short statements into separate sentences when no special effect is needed: ''I opened the door and I looked into the room'' (not *''I opened the door. And I looked into the room''). Combining sentences or starting with ''in addition'' or ''moreover'' is preferred in formal writing.\n\n{{m|en|and|And}} is often omitted for contextual effects of various kinds, especially between sequences of descriptive adjectives which can be separated by commas or simply by spaces\n\n<blockquote>(The teeming jerrybuilt dun-coloured traffic-ridden deafening city—Penelope Lively, 1987)</blockquote>\n\nIn U.S. financial contexts such as [[cheque|check]] writing, '''and''' is often proscribed within full dollar amounts, reserved for use only immediately before the cent value. For instance, $150 is written \"one hundred fifty\", whereas \"one hundred '''and''' fifty\" is arguably ambiguous and could be taken to mean $100.50 instead. Some even teach that '''and''' literally means a decimal point, although a standard writing would at least denote the fractional dollar value as hundredths, e.g. with \"/xx\".\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|used to connect two similar words or phrases}} {{l|en|as well as}}, {{l|en|together with}}, {{l|en|in addition to}}\n* {{sense|informal}} {{l|en|&}}, {{l|en|'n'}}, {{l|en|+}}\n* {{sense|in artist collaborations}} {{l|en|x}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en\n|Antigua and Barbuda\n|Bosnia and Herzegovina\n|French Southern and Antarctic Lands\n|fish and chips\n|piece and crisps\n|rock and roll\n|and all\n|and of course\n|and then everyone clapped\n|AND gate\n|Rhode Island and Providence Plantations\n|Saint Kitts and Nevis\n|Saint Pierre and Miquelon\n|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines\n|São Tomé and Príncipe\n|South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands\n|Turks and Caicos Islands\n|Trinidad and Tobago\n|Wallis and Futuna}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{see translation subpage|Conjunction}}\n\n=====See also=====\n{{col|en\n|false\n|if\n|iff\n|implies\n|nand\n|nor\n|not\n|or\n|true\n|xor\n}}\n\n=====See also=====\n* {{l|en|formal logic}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|second half of divided beat}}{{lb|en|music|often informal}} In [[rhythm]], the second half of a divided [[beat]].\n#: {{cot|en|e<id:music>|a<id:music>}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|author=Gordon Goodwin|title=Gordon Goodwin's Big Phat Band: Trumpet|page=51\n|passage=The same goes for measure 42, when you begin the phrase on the '''and''' of 1, because that kind of lick can easily bog down the time.}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{rfv|en}}\n{{inh+|en|enm|ande}}, from {{inh|en|ang|anda||grudge, enmity, malice, envy, hatred, anger, zeal, annoyance, vexation; zeal; injury, mischief; fear, horror}} and {{der|en|non|andi||breath, wind, spirit}}; both from {{der|en|gem-pro|*anadô||breath, anger, zeal}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₂enh₁-||to breathe, blow}}.\n\nCognate with {{cog|de|[[Ahnd]], [[And]]||woe, grief}}, {{cog|da|ånde||breath}}, {{cog|sv|[[anda]], [[ande]]||spirit, breath, wind, ingenuity, intellect}}, {{cog|is|andi||spirit}}, {{cog|sq|ëndë||pleasure, delight}}, {{cog|la|animus||spirit, soul}}. Related to {{m|en|onde}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|en|aynd|eynd}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|UK|_|dialectal}} [[breath|Breath]].\n# {{lb|en|UK|_|dialectal}} {{w|Sea smoke}}; [[steam fog]].\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{rfv|en}}\n{{inh+|en|enm|anden}}, from {{inh|en|ang|andian||to be envious or jealous, envy}} and {{der|en|non|anda||to breathe}}; both from {{der|en|gem-pro|*anadōną||to breathe, sputter}}. Cognate with {{cog|de|ahnden||to avenge, punish}}, {{cog|da|ånde||to breathe}}, {{cog|sv|andas||to breathe}}, {{cog|is|anda||to breathe}}. See above.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{l|en|eind}}, {{l|en|eynd}}, {{l|en|ein}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|UK|_|dialectal|intransitive}} To [[breathe]]; [[whisper]]; [[devise]]; [[imagine]].\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=adn|-dan|ADN|DAN|DNA|Dan|Dan.|NAD|NDA|dan|dna|nad}}\n\n{{cln|en|coordinating conjunctions|3-letter words}}\n\n==Azerbaijani==\n{{az-variant|анд|آند}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|az|trk-pro|*ānt|t=oath}}.<ref>{{R:trk-pro:SDM|*Ānt|293}}</ref> Cognate with {{cog|otk|𐰦}}, {{cog|tr|ant}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|az|[ɑnd]}}\n* {{audio|az|LL-Q9292 (aze)-Zardabi Bakuvi-and.wav|a=Baku}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{az-noun}}\n\n# [[oath]]\n#: {{syn|az|əhd}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{az-decl-noun|a|c}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|az|and içmək||to take an oath}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n==Danish==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|da|non|ǫnd}}, from {{inh|da|gem-pro|*anadz}}, cognate with {{cog|de|Ente}}, {{cog|nl|eend}}. The Germanic noun derives from {{inh|da|ine-pro|*h₂énh₂ts||duck}}, which is also the source of {{cog|la|anas}}, {{cog|grc|νῆττα}}, {{cog|lt|ántis}}, {{cog|sa|आति|tr=ātí}}.\n\nThe sense of \"false story\" is a {{semantic loan|da|fr|canard|nocap=1}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|da|/anˀ/|[ænˀ]}}\n* {{rhymes|da|and|s=1}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{da-noun|en|ænder}}\n\n# [[duck]] {{gloss|{{taxfmt|Anatinae|family}}}}\n# [[canard]] {{q|false or misleading report or story}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{da-decl|en|ænder|ænderne}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|da|anderik}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:DDO}}\n\n{{C|da|Ducks}}\n\n==Estonian==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|et|urj-fin-pro|*anti}}, from the root of {{m|et|andma}}. Cognate with {{cog|fi|anti}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{et-IPA|an'd}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{et-noun|anni|andi}}\n\n# [[offering]], [[gift]]\n# [[alms]], [[donation]]\n# [[giftedness]], [[talent]]\n# act of [[giving]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{et-decl2|anni|andi|andide|ande||andi|||andisid|type=paks}}\n\n==Fingallian==\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|gmw-fin|conjunction}}\n\n# {{l|en|and}}\n\n==Gothic==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{got-rom}}\n\n# {{romanization of|got|𐌰𐌽𐌳}}\n\n==Livonian==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymid|liv|gift}}\nFrom {{inh|liv|urj-fin-pro|*anti}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{liv-p}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|liv|noun}}\n\n# [[gift]], [[present]]\n# [[talent]], [[gift]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{liv-decl|94}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:liv:LEL|and}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{etymid|liv|S-give}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|liv|verb}}\n\n# {{liv-Salaca form of|andõ|t=to give}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:liv:LDW}}\n* {{R:liv:SLW}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|enm|id=conjunction|:inh|ang:and}}\nFrom {{inh|enm|ang|and}}, {{m|ang|ond}}, {{m|ang|end}}, from {{inh|enm|gmw-pro|*andi}}, from {{inh|enm|gem-pro|*andi}}, from {{inh|enm|ine-pro|*h₂énti}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|enm|annd|ant|an|en}}\n* {{alter|enm|⁊|&}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|enm|/and/}}\n* {{IPA|enm|/an/|/ɛn/|a=unstressed}}\n\n====Conjunction====\n{{head|enm|conjunction}}\n\n# {{l|en|and}}, {{l|en|and}} [[then]] {{gloss|connects two elements of a sentence}}\n#* {{RQ:Ormulum|d|3|url=https://digital.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/objects/90a06f70-880a-4b5b-bd30-798710afff11/surfaces/a2980d0a-ac52-4383-ba1b-bc0a6a6f567a/|Nu broþerr Ƿallꞇ͛. broþerͬ min. Affꞇ͛ þe flæsheſſ kĩde⹎ '''⁊''' broþerͬ mın ı crıſſtenndom. Þurrh fulluhht⹎<!--?--> '''⁊''' þurrh troꟕþe⹎ '''⁊''' broþerr mın ı ꟑodeſſ huſ {{...}}|Now, Brother Walter, my brother by blood relation '''and''' in Christendom, through baptism '''and''' faith, '''and''' my brother in God's house {{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-book|enm|year=c. 1340|title=w:Ayenbite of Inwyt|author=Dan Michel|chapter=Þe oþer Godes Heste|passage=Ac þe ilke / þet zuereþ hidousliche be god / oþer by his halȝen / '''and''' him to-breȝþ / '''and''' zayþ him sclondres / þet ne byeþ naȝt to zigge: þe ilke zeneȝeþ dyadliche {{...}}|translation=But one who / hideously swears by God / or by his emissaries / '''and''' who tears him apart / '''while''' saying to him lies / that shouldn't be said: they sin grievously. {{...}} }}\n#* {{quote-book|enm|year=c. 1380|title=Sir Firumbras|lines=4413–4414|passage=\"Lordes\", quaþ Richard, \"Buþ noȝt agast, Ac holdeþ forþ ȝour way / '''an''' hast & boldeliche doþ ȝour dede {{...}}\" |translation=\"Lords\", said Richard, \"Don't be frightened, but hold your way forwards / '''and''' quickly and boldy do your deed {{...}}\" }}\n#* {{RQ:Wycliffe NT Lichfield|book=Revelation|chapter=1|verse=8|leaf=117|side=v|passage=ȝhe amen / I am alpha '''⁊''' oo þe bigynnyng '''⁊''' þe ende ſeiþ þe loꝛd god þat is / '''⁊''' þat was. '''⁊''' that is to comynge almyȝti|translation=You, Amen! I am Alpha '''and''' O, the beginning '''and''' the end, says the Lord God; that is, that was, '''and''' that which will come, almighty.}}\n#* {{RQ:Chaucer Canterbury Tales|version=Hg|title=Prologue|folio=2|url=https://viewer.library.wales/4628556#?c=&m=&s=&cv=14|passage=Whan that Auerill w{{sup|t}} his shoures soote / The droghte of march hath &#42833;ced to the roote / '''And''' bathed euery veyne in swich lycour / Of which v̄tu engendred is the flour{{...}}|translation=When that April, with its sweet showers / Has pierced March's drought to the root / '''And''' bathed every vein in fluid such that / with its power, the flower is made{{...}}}}\n# [[however]], [[yet]], [[but]], [[though]]. [[while]]\n# [[if]], supposing that, [[whether]].\n# {{lb|enm|rare}} [[as|As]] [[though]], like, in a manner suggesting.\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|en|and}}\n* {{desc|sco|an}}\n* {{desc|yol|an|alts=1}}\n\n=====References=====\n* {{R:MED Online|entry=and|pos=conj. (& adv.)|id=MED1536|accessdate=2019-01-14}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}}\n\n# {{tlb|enm|Northern ME}} {{alt form|enm|onde|id=breath|t=breath}}\n\n==Norwegian Bokmål==\n{{wp|no:ender}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|nb|non|ǫnd}}, from {{inh|nb|gem-pro|*anadz}}, from {{inh|nb|ine-pro|*h₂énh₂ts||duck}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nb|/ɑnː/|/ɑnd/}}\n* {{audio|nb|no-and.ogg}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{nb-noun-c||end}}\n\n# a [[duck]]\n# [[canard]] (false or misleading report or story)\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|nb|Andeby||[[Duckburg]]}}\n* {{l|nb|andunge}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nb:OB}}\n\n{{C|nb|Birds}}\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nn|/an(d)/|[ɐ̞nd]|[ɐ̞nː]}} {{nn-pronu-note}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{wp|nn:}}\nFrom {{inh|nn|non|ǫnd}}, from {{inh|nn|gem-pro|*anadz}}, from {{inh|nn|ine-pro|*h₂énh₂ts||duck}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|nn|ond}}\n* {{alt|nn|ønd||dialectal}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{nn-noun-f1||end}}\n\n# a [[duck]] {{q|waterbird}}\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{nn-decl-f-c|and|end}}\n{{nn-decl-f-c-aasen|and|end|ond}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|nn\n|andebryst\n|Andeby\n|andebøle\n|andedam\n|andedun\n|andefamilie\n|andefugl\n|andeegg\n|andekall\n|andestegg\n|andunge\n|avisand\n|dykkand\n|fiskand\n|grasand\n|gravand\n|isand\n|krikkand\n|kvinand\n|laksand\n|stokkand\n|svartand\n|taffeland\n|toppand\n|villand\n}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{root|nn|ine-pro|*h₂enh₁-}}\nFrom {{inh|nn|non|ǫnd}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|nn|ond}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{nn-noun-f1}}\n\n# {{senseid|nn|breath}} [[breath]], [[spirit]]\n#: {{syn|nn|ande|pust}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|nn|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|nn|ande||imp}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nn:OB}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|nn|a=adn|and-|dan}}\n\n{{C|nn|Birds}}\n\n==Old English==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|ang|ond|end}}\n* {{alt|ang|ᚪᚾᛞ|ᛖᚾᛞ||{{w|Franks Casket}}}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|ang|:inh|gem-pro:*andi}}\nFrom {{inh|ang|gem-pro|[[*anda]], [[*andi]]}}, probably from {{der|ang|ine-pro|*h₂énti||facing opposite, near, in front of, before}}. Compare {{cog|ofs|and}}, {{cog|osx|endi}}, {{cog|goh|unti}}, {{cog|non|enn}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ang-IPA|and|}}\n* {{rhymes|ang|ɑnd|s=1}}\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|ang|conjunction}}\n\n# {{l|en|and}}\n#* {{quote-book|ang|text=''Þonne iċ mec onhebbe '''ond''' hī onhnīgaþ tō mē, moniġe mid miltse, þǣr iċ monnum sceal īċan upcyme ēadiġnesse.''|t=When I raise myself up '''and''' they bow down to me, many with mercy, then I shall increase rising of happiness for men.|title=Exeter Book Riddle 30|year=10th century|url=https://www.oldenglishaerobics.net/riddles.html#w0000250}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{l|ang|⁊}} {{qualifier|symbol}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desctree|enm|and}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{ang-adv}}\n\n# [[even]]; [[also]]\n\n==Old Frisian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|ofs|ande|ende}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|ofs|gem-pro|*andi}}, from {{inh|ofs|ine-pro|*h₂énti||facing opposite, near, in front of, before}}. Compare {{cog|ang|and}}, {{cog|osx|endi}}, {{cog|goh|unti}}, {{cog|non|enn}}.\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|ofs|conjunction}}\n\n# [[and#English|and]]\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|frr|än}}\n* {{desc|stq|un}}\n* {{desc|fy|en|in}}\n\n==Old Irish==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|sga|cel-pro|*andom}}, from {{der|sga|ine-pro|*h₁n̥dó}}. The adverbial sense of this term is the original one, and it has an etymology independent of {{m|sga|hi|i}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{sga-IPA}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|sga|prepositional pronoun}}\n\n# {{infl of|sga|hi||3|s|m//n|dat}}: [[in]] [[him]], [[in]] [[it]]\n#* {{RQ:sga-gloss|Ml|31|b|23}}\n#*: {{quote|sga|in bélrai .i. is '''and''' atá gním tengad isind huiliu labramar-ni|of speech, i.e. the action of the tongue is in it, in all that we say}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|sga|adverb}}\n\n# [[there]]\n#* {{RQ:sga:Glosses|Tur|110c}}\n#*: {{quote|sga|Ba bés leusom do·bertis dá boc leu dochum tempuil, ⁊ no·léicthe indala n‑ái fon díthrub co pecad in popuil, ⁊ do·bertis maldachta foir, ⁊ n⟨o⟩·oircthe didiu '''and''' ó popul tar cenn a pecthae ind aile.\n|It was a custom with them that two he-goats were brought by them to the temple, and one of the two of them was let go to the wilderness with the sin of the people, and curses were put upon him, and thereupon the other was slain '''there''' by the people for their sins.}}\n# [[then]], [[in that case]]\n#* {{RQ:sga:Glosses|Wb|4|a|27}}\n#*: {{quote|sga|Is '''and''' didiu for·téit {{m|la||spiritus}} ar n-énirti-ni in tain bes n-inun accobor lenn .i. la corp {{m|la||et}} anim {{m|la||et}} la spirut.\n|So it is '''then''' that the spirit helps our weakness when we have the same desire, to wit, body and soul and spirit.}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|mga|ann}}\n** {{desc|ga|ann}}\n** {{desc|gv|ayn}}\n** {{desc|gd|ann}}\n\n==Polish==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|pl|ampt||Eastern Greater Poland|Kłodawa}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|pl|:bor|de:Amt|text=+|tree=1}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{pl-pr|-|EGP=#}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{pl-noun|m-in}}\n\n# {{lb|pl|Eastern Greater Poland|Kłodawa|historic}} [[starost]]'s [[manor house]]\n#: {{uxa|pl|Byłem na '''andzie'''.|I was at the '''starost's manor house'''.}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:pl:Łopaciński:1893||692|5}}\n\n{{C|pl|Buildings|Housing}}\n\n==Scots==\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{h|sco|conj}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|sco|an}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n* While ''and'' is relatively often written due to English influence, it is seldom pronounced as such, making way for {{m|sco|an}}. <ref> https://dsl.ac.uk/entry/snd/and_conj1 </ref>\n\n====References====\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Swedish==\n{{wp|sv:}}\n[[File:Mallard_drake_swimming.jpg|thumb|300px|en '''and''' ({{l|sv|gräsand|gräs'''and'''}}) [a '''(wild) duck''' (mallard)] ]]\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|sv|non|ǫnd}}, from {{inh|sv|gem-pro|*anadz}}, from {{inh|sv|ine-pro|*h₂énh₂ts|t=duck}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|sv|/and/}}\n* {{audio|sv|Sv-and.ogg}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sv-noun|c}}\n\n# a wild [[duck]]\n#: {{ux|sv|mata '''änderna''' i parken|feed '''the ducks''' in the park}}\n## {{lb|sv|especially}} a [[mallard]]\n##: {{syn|sv|gräsand}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{sv-infl-noun-c-r|2=ande|3=ände}}\n\n====Related terms====\n{{col3\n|sv|andfågel\n|andjakt\n|andmat\n|andrake\n|andsträck\n|andunge\n|gräsand\n}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|sv|anka}} {{q|domesticated duck}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:svenska.se|so}}\n* {{R:svenska.se|saol}}\n* {{R:svenska.se|saob}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|sv|a=adn|-nad|Dan|dan}}\n\n{{cln|sv|nouns with irregular plurals}}\n{{C|sv|Ducks}}\n\n==Turkish==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|tr|noun}}\n\n# {{archaic form of|tr|ant|t=oath}}\n\n==Yola==\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|yol|conjunction}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|yol|an||and}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|title=GLOSSARY OF THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage=Jaude '''and''' maude.|translation=Crowds '''and''' throngs.}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|chapter=THE WEDDEEN O BALLYMORE|page=93|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage=\"steoute '''and''' straung,\"|translation=stout '''and''' strong;}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Poole 1867|page=49}}\n\n==Zealandic==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{dercat|zea|gem-pro|inh=1}}\n{{inh+|zea|dum|hant}}, from {{inh|zea|odt|hant}}, from {{inh|zea|gmw-pro|*handu}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{zea-noun|f}}\n\n# {{topics|zea|Body parts}} [[#English|hand]]\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{l|zea|'and}}"}}